WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.335 --> 00:00:04.430
Narrator: <i>In the criminal justice
system. the people are represented</i>

2
00:00:04.471 --> 00:00:07.031
<i>by two separate yet
equally important groups...</i>

3
00:00:07.074 --> 00:00:08.940
<i>The police who investigate crime</i>

4
00:00:08.976 --> 00:00:11.946
<i>and the district attorneys
who prosecute the offenders.</i>

5
00:00:11.979 --> 00:00:13.641
<i>These are their stories.</i>

6
00:00:15.682 --> 00:00:17.674
<i>(woman crying. chattering)</i>

7
00:00:20.521 --> 00:00:22.990
(arguing)

8
00:00:23.023 --> 00:00:26.016
H-o-r-t-o-n. that's the guy
you should've brought in here.

9
00:00:26.059 --> 00:00:28.995
Miss. I've been here 40 minutes.

10
00:00:29.029 --> 00:00:30.725
I just need to
know where she is.

11
00:00:30.764 --> 00:00:32.460
I told you before. sir.

12
00:00:32.499 --> 00:00:35.560
I have to check with
admitting. It's ridiculous.

13
00:00:35.602 --> 00:00:37.195
Nurse: <i>Get a doctor. stat!</i>

14
00:00:37.237 --> 00:00:39.900
Man: <i>We need some
help in here. please! Now!</i>

15
00:00:39.940 --> 00:00:41.875
She's turning blue.
She can't breathe!

16
00:00:41.909 --> 00:00:43.275
Get the ambu bag.

17
00:00:43.310 --> 00:00:45.870
No pulse. Call a code!

18
00:00:45.913 --> 00:00:47.745
Come on. let's go. move!

19
00:00:47.781 --> 00:00:50.080
I need a line in!

20
00:00:50.117 --> 00:00:52.814
Get the defibrillator.

21
00:00:52.853 --> 00:00:54.845
You knew that wasn't right.

22
00:01:00.394 --> 00:01:02.693
You can't go in there. sir.

23
00:01:02.729 --> 00:01:04.288
Call the guard. Sir!

24
00:01:06.633 --> 00:01:08.568
No pulse. Give her Epi IV.

25
00:01:16.810 --> 00:01:19.109
No response. Get me adrenaline.

26
00:01:19.146 --> 00:01:20.657
Excuse us. please.
Please wait outside.

27
00:01:20.681 --> 00:01:22.225
<i>We're doing everything
we can. What's going on?</i>

28
00:01:22.249 --> 00:01:24.013
Excuse us... Please.
that's my daughter.

29
00:01:24.051 --> 00:01:27.215
You can't come in here...
Don't even try. What's going on?

30
00:01:27.254 --> 00:01:29.120
The last blood gases.

31
00:01:31.325 --> 00:01:33.453
Let's call it.

32
00:01:33.493 --> 00:01:35.758
23:17.

33
00:01:35.796 --> 00:01:38.356
Oh. my God. What
the hell happened?

34
00:01:38.398 --> 00:01:39.676
Your daughter
had cardiac arrest.

35
00:01:39.700 --> 00:01:41.100
Resuscitate her. defib her!

36
00:01:41.134 --> 00:01:43.626
Please. please! Your
daughter is dead.

37
00:01:43.670 --> 00:01:45.536
Where are you
going? I don't get this.

38
00:01:45.572 --> 00:01:47.917
She only had a sore throat.
This is insane! Some help please!

39
00:01:47.941 --> 00:01:50.570
Come on. pal. let's go. No.
guys. she only had a sore throat!

40
00:01:50.611 --> 00:01:52.842
She didn't even have a fever!

41
00:01:52.879 --> 00:01:54.905
<i>She only came in
for a prescription.</i>

42
00:01:54.948 --> 00:01:56.041
<i>I don't understand. guys.</i>

43
00:01:57.050 --> 00:01:59.781
<i>(theme music playing)</i>

44
00:03:21.868 --> 00:03:24.599
<i>Where was she murdered?</i> I
told you. Urban Medical Center.

45
00:03:25.839 --> 00:03:28.331
I'm sorry. Mr. Morton.
I'm a little confused.

46
00:03:29.376 --> 00:03:31.811
Your daughter was
killed at the hospital?

47
00:03:31.845 --> 00:03:34.679
Yeah. in the emergency room. I
want to swear out a murder complaint

48
00:03:34.715 --> 00:03:36.377
against the resident
in charge of it.

49
00:03:37.517 --> 00:03:39.645
This resident was treating her?

50
00:03:39.686 --> 00:03:41.518
No. killing her.

51
00:03:42.622 --> 00:03:45.524
But she was at the
hospital for treatment?

52
00:03:45.559 --> 00:03:47.653
Yeah. a sore
throat. Muscle aches.

53
00:03:47.694 --> 00:03:49.322
She only went in
to get a prescription

54
00:03:49.362 --> 00:03:51.160
for some antibiotics.

55
00:03:53.366 --> 00:03:56.803
Sometimes people are a
lot sicker than they look.

56
00:03:56.837 --> 00:03:59.204
Listen to me. I was
a medic in Vietnam.

57
00:03:59.239 --> 00:04:01.037
I know who's
dying and who isn't.

58
00:04:01.074 --> 00:04:02.770
My daughter was not that sick.

59
00:04:02.809 --> 00:04:05.643
Somebody in that emergency
room did something that killed her.

60
00:04:05.679 --> 00:04:07.841
Who's he want to
bring charges against?

61
00:04:07.881 --> 00:04:10.350
The resident in charge
of the emergency room.

62
00:04:10.383 --> 00:04:12.181
Oh. come on. Max.

63
00:04:12.219 --> 00:04:14.552
People die in hospital
emergency rooms

64
00:04:14.588 --> 00:04:16.454
every hour of every day.

65
00:04:16.490 --> 00:04:19.722
That may indeed be
tragic. but it is not criminal.

66
00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:21.888
Unless somebody
was criminally negligent.

67
00:04:21.928 --> 00:04:23.954
How the hell would
Mr. Morton know

68
00:04:23.997 --> 00:04:25.488
if that had happened?

69
00:04:25.532 --> 00:04:27.228
He was a medic in Vietnam.

70
00:04:27.267 --> 00:04:29.532
He says she wasn't
sick enough to die.

71
00:04:30.837 --> 00:04:32.897
He was very convincing.

72
00:04:34.641 --> 00:04:36.371
I'm not saying no.

73
00:04:41.314 --> 00:04:44.910
I just had my first
day off in two weeks.

74
00:04:44.951 --> 00:04:47.978
There is a world out there.

75
00:04:48.021 --> 00:04:49.990
Logan: <i>You're the intern
who treated a young girl</i>

76
00:04:50.023 --> 00:04:52.686
<i>named Suzanne Morton?</i>

77
00:04:52.726 --> 00:04:55.662
Yeah. she's the last patient
I admitted before I took off.

78
00:04:55.695 --> 00:04:57.459
Bronchitis.

79
00:04:57.497 --> 00:04:59.625
She dramatized
her symptoms a bit.

80
00:04:59.666 --> 00:05:01.862
So I ordered a chest x-ray

81
00:05:01.902 --> 00:05:03.564
and put her aside to
wait for a bed. Why?

82
00:05:03.603 --> 00:05:06.573
Right now we're doing a
routine investigation of her death.

83
00:05:06.606 --> 00:05:08.472
Death?

84
00:05:09.476 --> 00:05:10.944
What. she died?

85
00:05:10.977 --> 00:05:12.969
You sound surprised.

86
00:05:16.416 --> 00:05:18.317
Don't people croak
here every day?

87
00:05:21.988 --> 00:05:23.820
She wasn't that sick.

88
00:05:24.991 --> 00:05:27.017
You don't die from bronchitis.

89
00:05:28.161 --> 00:05:29.595
Suzanne Morton.

90
00:05:29.629 --> 00:05:31.120
She had pneumonia.

91
00:05:31.164 --> 00:05:33.633
<i>The sputum examination and
blood culture were indicative.</i>

92
00:05:33.667 --> 00:05:35.966
We discussed it during rounds.

93
00:05:36.002 --> 00:05:37.470
Pneumonia. huh?

94
00:05:37.504 --> 00:05:39.302
A lot of people die
of that these days?

95
00:05:39.339 --> 00:05:42.969
When it's complicated by
chemical pneumonitis. sometimes.

96
00:05:43.009 --> 00:05:45.342
<i>Patient was feverish
and fell unconscious.</i>

97
00:05:45.378 --> 00:05:48.815
She must have aspirated some
of the contents of her stomach.

98
00:05:48.849 --> 00:05:50.875
Stomach acid and
lungs do not mix well.

99
00:05:50.917 --> 00:05:52.852
This can happen fast?

100
00:05:54.354 --> 00:05:56.516
Yes. it can. Excuse me.

101
00:05:57.691 --> 00:06:00.661
Hmm. Busy woman.

102
00:06:00.694 --> 00:06:04.825
Yeah. so busy she can't
even make eye contact.

103
00:06:04.865 --> 00:06:06.800
Suzanne Morton.

104
00:06:06.833 --> 00:06:09.064
Yes. if you see Mr. Morton.

105
00:06:09.102 --> 00:06:10.968
please extend my condolences.

106
00:06:11.004 --> 00:06:13.166
Dr. Raza. were you on
rounds when they reached her?

107
00:06:13.206 --> 00:06:15.107
Yes. yes. that is right.

108
00:06:15.141 --> 00:06:16.575
I came right away.

109
00:06:18.211 --> 00:06:20.874
Why? I didn't think
she was that sick.

110
00:06:20.914 --> 00:06:23.179
We hear bronchitis.
maybe pneumonia.

111
00:06:23.216 --> 00:06:24.616
No. no. no. She was very sick.

112
00:06:24.651 --> 00:06:26.429
She should've been in
the intensive care unit.

113
00:06:26.453 --> 00:06:29.423
Unfortunately
there were no beds.

114
00:06:30.590 --> 00:06:32.559
In my country. we accept death.

115
00:06:32.592 --> 00:06:35.562
But here. you're
expected to live forever.

116
00:06:37.330 --> 00:06:39.265
You ever hold a human
heart in your hands?

117
00:06:39.299 --> 00:06:41.359
Only mine.

118
00:06:42.736 --> 00:06:44.967
What year are you in? Third.

119
00:06:45.005 --> 00:06:46.769
We go hands on.

120
00:06:46.806 --> 00:06:49.332
Did you ever lay your
hands on Suzanne Morton?

121
00:06:49.376 --> 00:06:51.072
The pneumonia. yeah.

122
00:06:51.111 --> 00:06:53.239
I spent 40 minutes
trying to find an orderly

123
00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:55.044
to take her to intensive care.

124
00:06:55.081 --> 00:06:56.709
On the way back.

125
00:06:56.750 --> 00:06:58.446
I passed a gunshot
wound through the neck

126
00:06:58.485 --> 00:07:01.216
with a six-inch exit. You
ever see one of those?

127
00:07:01.254 --> 00:07:03.314
Yeah. well. they're
not so exciting

128
00:07:03.356 --> 00:07:05.484
when you run into
one in a crack house.

129
00:07:08.295 --> 00:07:09.923
Max: <i>Tell me some more.</i>

130
00:07:09.963 --> 00:07:11.625
This guy in the emergency room.

131
00:07:11.665 --> 00:07:13.293
must've been his
daughter who was sick.

132
00:07:13.333 --> 00:07:16.012
He was going nuts yelling why didn't
they do this. why didn't they do that?

133
00:07:16.036 --> 00:07:17.561
Sounded like he
knew his way around.

134
00:07:17.604 --> 00:07:18.867
Around the hospital?

135
00:07:18.905 --> 00:07:21.500
Around sick people.

136
00:07:21.541 --> 00:07:24.067
Those doctors?
Something wasn't right.

137
00:07:24.110 --> 00:07:25.635
the way they looked.

138
00:07:25.679 --> 00:07:27.807
What. worried? Excited?

139
00:07:28.949 --> 00:07:30.747
Embarrassed.

140
00:07:32.485 --> 00:07:34.477
Embarrassed.

141
00:07:36.990 --> 00:07:39.221
Does this make
sense to you. Max?

142
00:07:40.360 --> 00:07:42.261
Sure. She had bronchitis.
she had pneumonia.

143
00:07:42.295 --> 00:07:45.697
She was fine when she got here.
she was dying when she got here.

144
00:07:45.732 --> 00:07:47.496
God-like pronouncements

145
00:07:47.534 --> 00:07:49.526
sound like normal
medical procedure to me.

146
00:07:51.504 --> 00:07:53.598
So Max. what's your problem?

147
00:07:54.908 --> 00:07:56.308
Meaning?

148
00:07:56.343 --> 00:07:58.073
Meaning your attitude.

149
00:08:00.013 --> 00:08:01.982
'82.

150
00:08:02.015 --> 00:08:05.247
My partner and I go
into this fleabag SRO.

151
00:08:05.285 --> 00:08:07.777
To pick up some
junkie bank robber.

152
00:08:07.821 --> 00:08:09.255
I'm putting the cuffs on him.

153
00:08:09.289 --> 00:08:11.918
his girlfriend comes from
out of nowhere. jumps me.

154
00:08:11.958 --> 00:08:14.291
We're rolling around. I hit
my head against the radiator.

155
00:08:14.327 --> 00:08:17.491
<i>It hurt like hell.
but it's no big deal.</i>

156
00:08:18.932 --> 00:08:20.992
A week later

157
00:08:21.034 --> 00:08:23.026
I start slurring words.

158
00:08:26.539 --> 00:08:30.237
I go see a neurologist.
Quote. "Top guy in Manhattan."

159
00:08:31.978 --> 00:08:33.742
He looks at me.

160
00:08:33.780 --> 00:08:35.612
he says. "I want
you in the hospital.

161
00:08:35.648 --> 00:08:37.947
I'm going to do a CAT scan."

162
00:08:37.984 --> 00:08:40.112
Yeah. well. I would
definitely freak.

163
00:08:40.153 --> 00:08:42.088
<i>The next day. Dr. God comes in.</i>

164
00:08:42.122 --> 00:08:44.557
he says.

165
00:08:44.591 --> 00:08:48.187
"You have an inoperable
brain tumor in your cerebellum."

166
00:08:48.228 --> 00:08:50.129
He said it like
he was telling me

167
00:08:50.163 --> 00:08:52.223
they'd be serving
chicken for dinner.

168
00:08:53.266 --> 00:08:54.962
We decide to get
a second opinion.

169
00:08:55.001 --> 00:08:57.561
I go see another
"top neurologist."

170
00:08:57.604 --> 00:09:00.665
He does another
CAT scan. he comes in

171
00:09:00.707 --> 00:09:02.972
and says. "You <i>don't</i> have

172
00:09:03.009 --> 00:09:05.205
a brain tumor in
your cerebellum.

173
00:09:05.245 --> 00:09:07.908
you have a subdural
hematoma here."

174
00:09:07.947 --> 00:09:09.108
(chuckling)

175
00:09:11.117 --> 00:09:13.143
A month later. I was fine.

176
00:09:14.287 --> 00:09:17.689
Hey. at least he caught
the mistake. all right?

177
00:09:17.724 --> 00:09:19.090
(sighs)

178
00:09:19.125 --> 00:09:20.991
Yeah.

179
00:09:22.295 --> 00:09:24.958
And when they don't.
they just bury them.

180
00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:29.366
Dr. Auster will see you now.

181
00:09:30.437 --> 00:09:33.066
Let's go see the
Chief of Medicine.

182
00:09:33.106 --> 00:09:35.007
I'm sure he'll be God-like. too.

183
00:09:35.041 --> 00:09:38.808
A diagnostician
is like a detective.

184
00:09:40.146 --> 00:09:43.241
As a matter of fact. Conan
Doyle modeled Sherlock Holmes

185
00:09:43.283 --> 00:09:45.878
on Dr. Joseph Bell.

186
00:09:46.986 --> 00:09:48.887
You solve every
case you work on?

187
00:09:48.922 --> 00:09:50.948
We can tell a felony
from a traffic ticket.

188
00:09:50.990 --> 00:09:53.824
Look. a patient walks
in with a headache.

189
00:09:53.860 --> 00:09:55.761
She have a
subarachnoid hemorrhage.

190
00:09:55.795 --> 00:09:57.855
a berry aneurysm.

191
00:09:57.897 --> 00:10:00.230
a retro-orbital tumor.

192
00:10:00.266 --> 00:10:02.701
or does she just
have a headache?

193
00:10:02.735 --> 00:10:04.761
Do you give her an aspirin.

194
00:10:04.804 --> 00:10:06.568
or do you saw open her skull?

195
00:10:06.606 --> 00:10:09.337
You make this
speech at funerals?

196
00:10:09.375 --> 00:10:12.209
<i>I saw that girl in the
emergency room on rounds.</i>

197
00:10:12.245 --> 00:10:15.181
She was in the hands
of competent staff.

198
00:10:15.215 --> 00:10:17.150
The girl is dead.

199
00:10:17.183 --> 00:10:19.584
<i>People like to believe that
medicine is pure science.</i>

200
00:10:19.619 --> 00:10:22.088
Medicine is a science.

201
00:10:22.122 --> 00:10:25.183
but doctors know
it's also a lottery.

202
00:10:26.626 --> 00:10:29.562
See what I mean? The
guy's Chief of Medicine.

203
00:10:29.596 --> 00:10:31.656
and all he can come up with is.

204
00:10:31.698 --> 00:10:33.690
"It's a lottery."

205
00:10:36.503 --> 00:10:39.098
Proceed. Sherlock.

206
00:10:47.780 --> 00:10:50.875
What do you do when you
make a mistake? Use white-out?

207
00:10:50.917 --> 00:10:53.182
Huh-uh. You cross
it out and initial it.

208
00:10:53.219 --> 00:10:55.051
This ain't no letter
to Dear Abby.

209
00:10:55.088 --> 00:10:56.681
These charts got
to show everything

210
00:10:56.723 --> 00:10:59.283
or there could be serious
legal repercussions.

211
00:10:59.325 --> 00:11:02.659
Serious legal repercussions.
that's what we have here.

212
00:11:02.695 --> 00:11:06.154
Somebody used white-out
on Suzanne Morton's chart.

213
00:11:10.837 --> 00:11:13.136
Now. on top of the white-out

214
00:11:13.173 --> 00:11:14.732
it says acetaminophen...

215
00:11:14.774 --> 00:11:16.367
A common. everyday painkiller.

216
00:11:16.409 --> 00:11:18.742
But underneath the white-out

217
00:11:18.778 --> 00:11:22.579
it said. "meperidine."

218
00:11:22.615 --> 00:11:23.810
It's a narcotic.

219
00:11:23.850 --> 00:11:26.376
Big difference.
Third-rate cover up.

220
00:11:26.419 --> 00:11:29.480
Whoever did it probably wasn't
expecting an investigation.

221
00:11:29.522 --> 00:11:33.425
Whoever wrote meperidine
also wrote acetaminophen.

222
00:11:34.594 --> 00:11:36.722
Look at the E's
in acetaminophen.

223
00:11:36.763 --> 00:11:39.631
See the kind of like
cursive penmanship

224
00:11:39.666 --> 00:11:41.862
and English style
popular in the colonies.

225
00:11:41.901 --> 00:11:44.632
You see the shape and
the angle of the loop?

226
00:11:44.671 --> 00:11:48.005
Now it matches
notations that were here.

227
00:11:48.041 --> 00:11:51.409
here. and here.

228
00:11:51.444 --> 00:11:53.504
All of them initialed "ER."

229
00:11:54.514 --> 00:11:56.278
Emergency room?

230
00:11:56.316 --> 00:11:58.342
Ekballa Raza.

231
00:12:00.486 --> 00:12:02.097
Doctor: <i>She had a headache
and a low-grade fever.</i>

232
00:12:02.121 --> 00:12:03.612
Nothing more.

233
00:12:03.656 --> 00:12:06.285
I gave her an antibiotic
and an antihistamine.

234
00:12:06.326 --> 00:12:08.625
No doctor would've
done anything more.

235
00:12:09.796 --> 00:12:12.265
Sounds like you're
on solid ground.

236
00:12:13.833 --> 00:12:16.393
Her psychiatrist had
her on phenelzine sulfate.

237
00:12:17.403 --> 00:12:18.928
She was seeing a shrink?

238
00:12:18.972 --> 00:12:21.532
She'd been depressed
since her mother's death.

239
00:12:21.574 --> 00:12:23.805
When did that happen?

240
00:12:24.811 --> 00:12:26.143
Last year.

241
00:12:26.179 --> 00:12:29.047
She developed peritonitis
after her hysterectomy.

242
00:12:33.286 --> 00:12:36.279
This... phenel... what is it?

243
00:12:36.322 --> 00:12:38.223
Phenelzine... Nurse: <i>Doctor?</i>

244
00:12:38.258 --> 00:12:41.160
Miss Rossi is ready.

245
00:12:41.194 --> 00:12:43.629
Thank you. Phenelzine sulfate.

246
00:12:43.663 --> 00:12:45.029
An anti-depressant.

247
00:12:45.064 --> 00:12:46.532
A strong one.

248
00:12:50.536 --> 00:12:52.835
The patient died.
but don't worry.

249
00:12:52.872 --> 00:12:56.274
the doctor is doing just fine.

250
00:12:58.778 --> 00:13:02.271
Okay. the tox screen
shows acetaminophen.

251
00:13:02.315 --> 00:13:05.376
It shows aspirin. and it
shows an antihistamine.

252
00:13:05.418 --> 00:13:07.751
So there's no sign
of meperidine?

253
00:13:07.787 --> 00:13:10.450
Huh-uh. We ran the standard
gas and chromatography.

254
00:13:10.490 --> 00:13:13.119
We know the girl was on
something called phenelzine.

255
00:13:13.159 --> 00:13:15.128
Not a trace.

256
00:13:15.161 --> 00:13:18.461
Meperidine. phenelzine.
recreational drugs.

257
00:13:18.498 --> 00:13:19.966
Do another tox screen.

258
00:13:19.999 --> 00:13:22.161
I think you're
wasting your nickel.

259
00:13:23.903 --> 00:13:26.634
Nobody takes meperidine
and phenelzine...

260
00:13:26.673 --> 00:13:28.972
unless they want to
risk ending up here.

261
00:13:29.008 --> 00:13:31.534
They can be a fatal combination.

262
00:13:36.582 --> 00:13:38.483
I was exhausted.

263
00:13:38.518 --> 00:13:40.783
I'd just came off
the cancer ward.

264
00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:42.379
I wrote meperidine
without thinking.

265
00:13:42.422 --> 00:13:43.856
But I gave her acetaminophen.

266
00:13:43.890 --> 00:13:46.155
What about the white-out?

267
00:13:47.560 --> 00:13:49.859
There is paperwork required
when you write a narcotic

268
00:13:49.896 --> 00:13:51.421
and I did not
have time for that.

269
00:13:52.498 --> 00:13:54.023
Dr. Raza.

270
00:13:54.067 --> 00:13:56.002
you just confessed

271
00:13:56.035 --> 00:13:58.197
to falsifying hospital records.

272
00:13:58.237 --> 00:14:00.638
That's a class E felony.

273
00:14:02.475 --> 00:14:04.535
Look. when they look at me here.

274
00:14:04.577 --> 00:14:06.136
they see an Indian or a Paki...

275
00:14:06.179 --> 00:14:07.613
They don't even
know the difference.

276
00:14:07.647 --> 00:14:09.878
We're all supposed
to be bad doctors.

277
00:14:09.916 --> 00:14:13.648
You ask anybody. I have to be
twice as good as everybody else

278
00:14:13.686 --> 00:14:16.554
just so they will think I am
<i>as</i> good as everybody else.

279
00:14:18.024 --> 00:14:21.620
My children want to stay in this
country. my wife wants to stay.

280
00:14:21.661 --> 00:14:25.530
And to stay. all I have to do
is to be perfect all the time.

281
00:14:25.565 --> 00:14:29.024
Well. you fell a little
short of perfection

282
00:14:29.068 --> 00:14:31.560
on Suzanne Morton's chart.

283
00:14:31.604 --> 00:14:33.903
It was a simple mistake. Really?

284
00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:36.774
If the toxicologist
finds meperidine

285
00:14:36.809 --> 00:14:38.744
in Suzanne Morton's body.

286
00:14:38.778 --> 00:14:40.974
you'll be lucky if
you're only deported.

287
00:14:41.013 --> 00:14:42.845
P.A.: <i>Dr. Fleming.
please report to admitting</i>

288
00:14:42.882 --> 00:14:45.545
<i>in the Comprehensive
Cancer Care Center.</i>

289
00:14:45.585 --> 00:14:47.417
Have fun.

290
00:14:47.453 --> 00:14:49.183
Thanks.

291
00:14:50.189 --> 00:14:52.681
Max. dig this.

292
00:14:52.725 --> 00:14:54.751
Now here's a guy...

293
00:14:55.762 --> 00:14:57.424
swallowed his false teeth

294
00:14:57.463 --> 00:14:59.125
and they bit through
his intestines.

295
00:14:59.165 --> 00:15:00.394
(laughs)

296
00:15:00.433 --> 00:15:02.334
What did Dr. Raza prescribe.

297
00:15:02.368 --> 00:15:04.428
a good flossing?

298
00:15:04.470 --> 00:15:05.768
Oh. here we go.

299
00:15:05.805 --> 00:15:09.333
Mistake. crossed out. initialed.

300
00:15:10.376 --> 00:15:11.935
Same here.

301
00:15:11.978 --> 00:15:13.947
Look at this. we could
be holding in our hands

302
00:15:13.980 --> 00:15:15.642
the evidence to a mass murder.

303
00:15:15.681 --> 00:15:17.274
and we wouldn't even know it.

304
00:15:17.316 --> 00:15:18.944
Yeah. all these have

305
00:15:18.985 --> 00:15:22.114
evening rounds at 6:00 to 6:30.

306
00:15:22.155 --> 00:15:24.920
and the night that
Suzanne Morton died

307
00:15:24.957 --> 00:15:27.188
rounds were after 9:00.

308
00:15:28.428 --> 00:15:31.523
If you hear hoofbeats.
it's probably a horse.

309
00:15:31.564 --> 00:15:33.260
not a zebra.

310
00:15:34.700 --> 00:15:37.295
Old medical school saying...

311
00:15:37.336 --> 00:15:41.000
"Students tend to find exotic
diseases in ordinary symptoms."

312
00:15:41.040 --> 00:15:43.532
They need to be reminded
that most things are

313
00:15:43.576 --> 00:15:45.044
what they appear to be.

314
00:15:45.077 --> 00:15:48.172
You gentlemen
are on a zebra hunt.

315
00:15:49.482 --> 00:15:52.646
Either a zebra or a
horse using white-out.

316
00:15:52.685 --> 00:15:54.153
(chuckling)

317
00:15:54.187 --> 00:15:56.122
Or maybe Dr. Raza made
a mistake in the chart.

318
00:15:56.155 --> 00:15:58.886
Maybe he made a mistake
in the emergency room.

319
00:15:58.925 --> 00:16:00.587
No.

320
00:16:00.626 --> 00:16:02.959
You trust Dr. Raza. don't you?

321
00:16:02.995 --> 00:16:04.793
I offered him a job.

322
00:16:04.831 --> 00:16:07.300
Wrote a letter to
Immigration this morning.

323
00:16:08.935 --> 00:16:11.666
Strange time to
be hiring the guy.

324
00:16:11.704 --> 00:16:13.673
A good doctor...

325
00:16:13.706 --> 00:16:16.039
is a good doctor.

326
00:16:17.143 --> 00:16:19.044
Max: <i>What time were
rounds that night?</i>

327
00:16:19.078 --> 00:16:21.104
Sometime after 6:00.

328
00:16:21.147 --> 00:16:23.241
They stand around gabbing
and we're trying to keep

329
00:16:23.282 --> 00:16:25.808
some poor jerk from
bleeding to death.

330
00:16:27.954 --> 00:16:30.321
So what happened that night?
Why were rounds so late?

331
00:16:30.356 --> 00:16:31.847
We waited for the
Chief of Medicine.

332
00:16:31.891 --> 00:16:33.120
Dr. Auster.

333
00:16:33.159 --> 00:16:35.754
God on high descending.

334
00:16:35.795 --> 00:16:37.787
Well. he descended late.

335
00:16:37.830 --> 00:16:39.799
He said he'd been
delayed at some...

336
00:16:39.832 --> 00:16:42.097
retirement party for
one of the service chiefs.

337
00:16:42.134 --> 00:16:45.036
<i>Seemed like Dr. Auster
had a good time.</i>

338
00:16:45.071 --> 00:16:46.937
What do you mean?

339
00:16:48.541 --> 00:16:51.272
It smelled like he
had been drinking.

340
00:16:59.151 --> 00:17:02.519
The hospital wanted to
lay out cheese in a can

341
00:17:02.555 --> 00:17:04.786
and white wine from Bulgaria.

342
00:17:04.824 --> 00:17:07.623
So I had the party catered.

343
00:17:07.660 --> 00:17:09.128
Duck liver paté.

344
00:17:09.161 --> 00:17:11.153
Beluga malossal caviar.

345
00:17:11.197 --> 00:17:12.995
Oh. yes.

346
00:17:13.032 --> 00:17:15.433
Anesthesiology has
been very good to me.

347
00:17:16.536 --> 00:17:19.096
Did Dr. Auster have a good time?

348
00:17:19.138 --> 00:17:20.629
Oh. I hope so.

349
00:17:20.673 --> 00:17:23.575
The caviar cost
400 bucks a pound.

350
00:17:23.609 --> 00:17:25.271
Did Dr. Auster have a drink?

351
00:17:25.311 --> 00:17:27.371
Oh. yes. That's why I had bar.

352
00:17:27.413 --> 00:17:30.406
Happy Hour catering.
25 bucks a head.

353
00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:36.082
Max: You guys just
supply bartenders?

354
00:17:36.122 --> 00:17:38.216
We supply bartenders.
barmaids if you want 'em.

355
00:17:38.257 --> 00:17:40.226
ice. glasses. napkins. mixers.

356
00:17:40.259 --> 00:17:42.490
Booze? You supply. you save.

357
00:17:42.528 --> 00:17:43.860
You work the hospital job?

358
00:17:43.896 --> 00:17:47.128
I was there. Two waitresses
and Rory. another bartender.

359
00:17:47.166 --> 00:17:49.226
Remember this guy?

360
00:17:50.236 --> 00:17:51.864
<i>Yeah. Jim.</i>

361
00:17:51.904 --> 00:17:55.272
No. Ed. Edward Auster.

362
00:17:55.308 --> 00:17:57.402
No. no. Jim. Green.

363
00:17:58.844 --> 00:18:01.439
The bourbon?
That's what he drank.

364
00:18:01.480 --> 00:18:03.972
On the rocks. One
every five minutes.

365
00:18:05.017 --> 00:18:06.417
I can smell it.

366
00:18:06.452 --> 00:18:07.977
Somebody gave
her the wrong drugs.

367
00:18:08.020 --> 00:18:10.080
I don't know if it was
Gunga Din or Auster.

368
00:18:10.122 --> 00:18:12.557
but one of them
screwed the pooch.

369
00:18:14.126 --> 00:18:16.561
Mike. you look like
you got a problem.

370
00:18:19.098 --> 00:18:21.567
All I know about
hospitals is that my father

371
00:18:21.601 --> 00:18:22.967
is still walking today

372
00:18:23.002 --> 00:18:25.733
because he had a heart
transplant in one seven years ago.

373
00:18:26.772 --> 00:18:28.104
(sighs)

374
00:18:28.140 --> 00:18:30.609
I'm not saying all
doctors are bad.

375
00:18:30.643 --> 00:18:33.613
99% of them are solid pros.

376
00:18:33.646 --> 00:18:37.640
It's the rotten 1%. to
quote our friend Auster.

377
00:18:37.683 --> 00:18:40.585
that make it a lottery.
You bet your life.

378
00:18:40.620 --> 00:18:43.488
Come on. Max. you ain't
exactly a fan of the profession.

379
00:18:43.522 --> 00:18:46.014
I just want them held
to the same standards

380
00:18:46.058 --> 00:18:47.720
that cops are when
somebody gets shot

381
00:18:47.760 --> 00:18:49.456
or pilots when there's a crash.

382
00:18:49.495 --> 00:18:51.088
Yeah. and that's
what bothers me.

383
00:18:51.130 --> 00:18:54.294
Listen. Say I'm out with Maggie.

384
00:18:54.333 --> 00:18:56.996
we're having dinner. I
have a few pops. okay?

385
00:18:57.036 --> 00:18:59.005
Mm-hmm. go on. <i>I
look out the window.</i>

386
00:18:59.038 --> 00:19:00.563
<i>I see someone getting mugged.</i>

387
00:19:00.606 --> 00:19:03.838
I run out. pull my service
revolver out of my sock.

388
00:19:03.876 --> 00:19:05.538
I yell. "Halt."

389
00:19:05.578 --> 00:19:08.275
Now one of the muggers
reaches into his pocket.

390
00:19:08.314 --> 00:19:10.180
takes something
out. turns around.

391
00:19:10.216 --> 00:19:12.447
Pop. I blow him away.

392
00:19:12.485 --> 00:19:15.080
Yeah. but the
something ain't a weapon.

393
00:19:15.121 --> 00:19:17.681
It's the victim's wallet.

394
00:19:17.723 --> 00:19:19.919
That is still a totally
righteous shoot.

395
00:19:19.959 --> 00:19:22.292
You know that. I know that.

396
00:19:22.328 --> 00:19:24.923
Internal affairs smells
liquor on my breath.

397
00:19:24.964 --> 00:19:26.660
they crucify me.

398
00:19:30.636 --> 00:19:32.628
I got to tell you this.

399
00:19:32.672 --> 00:19:33.935
that's how this feels to me.

400
00:19:33.973 --> 00:19:37.034
There's a difference
between a few pops

401
00:19:37.076 --> 00:19:38.601
and a bourbon
every five minutes.

402
00:19:38.644 --> 00:19:40.545
Come on. the kid's exaggerating.

403
00:19:40.579 --> 00:19:42.605
Maybe he wasn't.

404
00:19:42.648 --> 00:19:46.312
No one said Auster
looked or acted drunk.

405
00:19:46.352 --> 00:19:48.321
They smelled it on his breath.

406
00:19:50.990 --> 00:19:54.188
You know looking and
acting drunk don't mean squat.

407
00:19:56.462 --> 00:19:58.590
What are you guys talking about?

408
00:20:01.500 --> 00:20:03.867
Back when Max
and I were partners.

409
00:20:06.005 --> 00:20:08.270
I had a little bit of
a drinking problem.

410
00:20:09.475 --> 00:20:12.502
Well finally he told me
he wouldn't partner with me

411
00:20:13.512 --> 00:20:15.344
unless I went to AA.

412
00:20:17.850 --> 00:20:19.409
And?

413
00:20:19.452 --> 00:20:21.478
And I told him to mind
his own freaking business.

414
00:20:23.723 --> 00:20:26.192
I was under control. I
knew what I was doing.

415
00:20:26.225 --> 00:20:28.751
I was just a social drinker.

416
00:20:30.229 --> 00:20:32.357
He made me so damn mad.

417
00:20:32.398 --> 00:20:34.867
I went out and I had
a few social drinks.

418
00:20:37.336 --> 00:20:39.601
A couple hours later.

419
00:20:39.638 --> 00:20:42.107
I was standing in the
middle of Lexington Avenue.

420
00:20:42.141 --> 00:20:44.133
not looking or acting drunk.

421
00:20:45.377 --> 00:20:47.812
but I had my gun
pointed at a taxi driver

422
00:20:47.847 --> 00:20:50.146
because I didn't like the
way he was honking his horn.

423
00:20:53.786 --> 00:20:55.948
That night I went
to my first meeting...

424
00:20:58.157 --> 00:21:00.683
and I've been sober ever since.

425
00:21:09.268 --> 00:21:11.294
Get back to the hospital.

426
00:21:11.337 --> 00:21:14.000
and twist a few people. huh?

427
00:21:14.039 --> 00:21:17.532
I'm begging you. don't
make me torpedo my career.

428
00:21:18.844 --> 00:21:20.506
We need a second witness.

429
00:21:20.546 --> 00:21:22.014
Hmm?

430
00:21:23.015 --> 00:21:24.779
<i>Look.</i>

431
00:21:24.817 --> 00:21:27.343
<i>Auster forgets more
every week than I know.</i>

432
00:21:28.854 --> 00:21:30.880
I came to New
York because of him.

433
00:21:30.923 --> 00:21:33.051
Do you know what it means
to be able to say I studied

434
00:21:33.092 --> 00:21:34.526
under Dr. Edward Auster?

435
00:21:37.096 --> 00:21:39.964
He could destroy
the rest of my career.

436
00:21:41.066 --> 00:21:42.864
What career?

437
00:21:51.710 --> 00:21:53.201
He was drunk.

438
00:22:07.593 --> 00:22:09.892
The girl had muscle pains.

439
00:22:09.929 --> 00:22:12.421
The doctor ordered meperidine

440
00:22:12.464 --> 00:22:15.628
and the resident said
something about phenelzine.

441
00:22:15.668 --> 00:22:18.228
I-I-I don't think he even heard.

442
00:22:19.371 --> 00:22:21.636
He took the meperidine.
he injected it himself.

443
00:22:21.674 --> 00:22:23.233
What. no one tried to stop him?

444
00:22:23.275 --> 00:22:26.439
What are we going to do. wrestle
Dr. Edward Auster to the floor?

445
00:22:27.847 --> 00:22:29.543
I-I didn't even
know he was wrong.

446
00:22:29.582 --> 00:22:31.813
You know now.

447
00:22:33.152 --> 00:22:37.089
Now we have to get approval
from an Executive Assistant DA.

448
00:22:37.122 --> 00:22:39.057
Stone's the boss. What
do you want me to do?

449
00:22:39.091 --> 00:22:40.650
This case is
politically sensitive.

450
00:22:40.693 --> 00:22:43.492
It gets tougher
all the time. Mike.

451
00:22:43.529 --> 00:22:46.624
The David’s kid already
made the turn once.

452
00:22:46.665 --> 00:22:49.499
He said flat out.
"Auster was drunk."

453
00:22:49.535 --> 00:22:53.028
Stone: <i>I want to go in with
more than a nervous resident.</i>

454
00:22:54.406 --> 00:22:57.205
The bartender says Auster
drank like a fish at the party.

455
00:22:59.211 --> 00:23:01.578
If the resident testifies.

456
00:23:02.815 --> 00:23:04.443
there's a good chance we get

457
00:23:04.483 --> 00:23:06.952
the rest of the ER
team to follow suit.

458
00:23:08.654 --> 00:23:10.350
Pick him up.

459
00:23:11.357 --> 00:23:13.223
P.A.: <i>Dr. Demacus to CCU.</i>

460
00:23:13.259 --> 00:23:15.626
<i>Dr. Demacus to CCU. please.</i>

461
00:23:15.661 --> 00:23:16.959
(laughing)

462
00:23:16.996 --> 00:23:20.398
See we did a procedure
called balloon angioplasty.

463
00:23:20.432 --> 00:23:22.367
Woman: <i>Oh. But the pain?</i>

464
00:23:22.401 --> 00:23:24.495
No. no. I don't
think it'll come back.

465
00:23:24.536 --> 00:23:27.404
I'm not saying that you
could take up racquetball.

466
00:23:27.439 --> 00:23:29.271
but you will be able
to walk. climb stairs.

467
00:23:29.308 --> 00:23:30.640
and swim.

468
00:23:30.676 --> 00:23:32.235
Thank you.

469
00:23:33.345 --> 00:23:36.042
Guess we won't need our guns.

470
00:23:36.081 --> 00:23:37.879
Edward Auster...

471
00:23:41.287 --> 00:23:43.756
We have a warrant
for your arrest.

472
00:23:49.762 --> 00:23:51.924
Practicing medicine drunk.

473
00:23:51.964 --> 00:23:54.399
It's not prosecuted much.
We're going to have...

474
00:23:54.433 --> 00:23:56.077
First in his class at
Harvard Medical School.

475
00:23:56.101 --> 00:23:58.832
Residency and fellowship...
Say hello to Phillip Nevins.

476
00:23:58.871 --> 00:24:00.169
Dr. Ross' attorney.

477
00:24:01.974 --> 00:24:04.466
Author of the classic
textbook in cardiology.

478
00:24:04.510 --> 00:24:06.706
winner of the Lasker
award for medical research.

479
00:24:06.745 --> 00:24:08.407
published 175 journal articles.

480
00:24:08.447 --> 00:24:09.642
Does he walk on water?

481
00:24:09.682 --> 00:24:11.844
The trash that you
people usually prosecute

482
00:24:11.884 --> 00:24:13.785
can't murder fast enough
to kill as many people

483
00:24:13.819 --> 00:24:15.788
as Edward Auster has saved.

484
00:24:15.821 --> 00:24:19.053
Now I'm just trying to save
you from a mistaken perspective.

485
00:24:20.059 --> 00:24:21.527
Failing to perceive

486
00:24:21.560 --> 00:24:23.495
a substantial and
unjustified risk

487
00:24:23.529 --> 00:24:25.395
that might cause
Suzanne Morton's death...

488
00:24:25.431 --> 00:24:26.865
Criminally negligent homicide.

489
00:24:26.899 --> 00:24:28.731
Consciously disregarding

490
00:24:28.767 --> 00:24:30.759
that substantial
and unjustified risk...

491
00:24:30.803 --> 00:24:32.635
Manslaughter two.

492
00:24:36.008 --> 00:24:38.000
See you in court. Stone.

493
00:24:39.678 --> 00:24:41.977
Nevins is going to
flood the witness stand

494
00:24:42.014 --> 00:24:44.711
with famous doctors
swearing that Auster

495
00:24:44.750 --> 00:24:47.310
is a cross between Albert
Schweitzer and Albert Einstein.

496
00:24:47.353 --> 00:24:49.845
And we've got a father who
was a medic 25 years ago?

497
00:24:49.888 --> 00:24:51.652
Morton took on heavy odds.

498
00:24:51.690 --> 00:24:53.625
Maybe we can even them out.

499
00:24:53.659 --> 00:24:56.026
I want you to interview
people who know Auster.

500
00:24:57.896 --> 00:24:59.865
So you're the dipstick

501
00:24:59.898 --> 00:25:01.662
who's prosecuting Bud Auster.

502
00:25:01.700 --> 00:25:04.363
Is that what you call Dr. Auster
around the fishing hole?

503
00:25:04.403 --> 00:25:06.463
It's what I've called him
since the second grade.

504
00:25:07.773 --> 00:25:10.038
Some people do things.

505
00:25:10.075 --> 00:25:12.067
and others...

506
00:25:12.111 --> 00:25:13.704
What do you and Auster do?

507
00:25:13.746 --> 00:25:16.147
We catch trout in Maine.

508
00:25:16.181 --> 00:25:17.843
Last time was in June.

509
00:25:18.851 --> 00:25:20.285
We sleep in the woods.

510
00:25:20.319 --> 00:25:22.447
tell each other we're just
as young as we used to be.

511
00:25:22.488 --> 00:25:26.186
And drink. Somebody pass
a law against drunk fishing?

512
00:25:30.496 --> 00:25:32.397
I first admired America

513
00:25:32.431 --> 00:25:34.662
when I saw "Judgment
at Nuremberg."

514
00:25:34.700 --> 00:25:37.260
Everybody pays for their crimes.

515
00:25:39.505 --> 00:25:41.770
I never thought it would be me.

516
00:25:43.675 --> 00:25:47.043
There'll be no prosecution
if you testify against Auster.

517
00:25:48.247 --> 00:25:50.443
And no job.

518
00:25:50.482 --> 00:25:52.917
I got to love America.

519
00:25:52.951 --> 00:25:54.476
and leave it.

520
00:25:56.688 --> 00:25:58.987
<i>Two or three times each month</i>

521
00:25:59.024 --> 00:26:00.356
<i>he calls. says he's coming.</i>

522
00:26:00.392 --> 00:26:02.293
<i>He's always late
because he's drunk.</i>

523
00:26:02.327 --> 00:26:04.819
You know what they
call those rounds?

524
00:26:06.065 --> 00:26:07.533
Liver rounds.

525
00:26:08.534 --> 00:26:10.127
Everyone knew.

526
00:26:10.169 --> 00:26:13.401
Suzanne Morton
did have pneumonia.

527
00:26:13.439 --> 00:26:15.408
And Dr. Auster
did tell you to lie.

528
00:26:17.943 --> 00:26:21.141
I have flexible
hours in my training.

529
00:26:22.815 --> 00:26:25.910
Do you know how important
that is when you're raising a child?

530
00:26:25.951 --> 00:26:27.544
That's non-responsive. Doctor.

531
00:26:27.586 --> 00:26:30.454
Auster didn't act drunk.

532
00:26:30.489 --> 00:26:32.048
He never acted drunk.

533
00:26:32.091 --> 00:26:33.787
But he was drunk. wasn't he?

534
00:26:33.826 --> 00:26:36.557
He was always
drunk on liver rounds.

535
00:26:37.996 --> 00:26:39.965
<i>Wasn't he?</i>

536
00:26:41.366 --> 00:26:43.699
And he did tell
you to lie. didn't he?

537
00:26:52.611 --> 00:26:54.603
That poor girl.

538
00:26:54.646 --> 00:26:57.241
All she needed was some aspirin

539
00:26:57.282 --> 00:26:59.183
and an antibiotic.

540
00:27:01.220 --> 00:27:03.052
Am I going to lose my license?

541
00:27:05.457 --> 00:27:07.949
That's not my decision. Doctor.

542
00:27:07.993 --> 00:27:10.462
However I will give you immunity

543
00:27:10.496 --> 00:27:12.624
from prosecution for conspiracy

544
00:27:12.664 --> 00:27:14.132
if you testify.

545
00:27:18.003 --> 00:27:21.303
You suspect. you know.
but what are you going to do?

546
00:27:21.340 --> 00:27:23.866
Contact the medical
society? Sure.

547
00:27:23.909 --> 00:27:26.378
Intern Stephen Simonson
wishes to file a complaint

548
00:27:26.411 --> 00:27:28.971
against the leading
cardiologist in the United States?

549
00:27:31.817 --> 00:27:34.787
Look. I admitted Suzanne Morton.

550
00:27:34.820 --> 00:27:36.880
It looks like I
blew the diagnosis.

551
00:27:36.922 --> 00:27:39.323
Is that what's bothering you?

552
00:27:46.398 --> 00:27:48.629
Look.

553
00:27:48.667 --> 00:27:50.329
six months ago

554
00:27:50.369 --> 00:27:52.304
I get this guy.
he's 25 years old.

555
00:27:52.337 --> 00:27:53.537
he's basically healthy. right?

556
00:27:53.572 --> 00:27:56.872
He walks in with the
worst headache in his life.

557
00:27:56.909 --> 00:27:58.901
His neck is sore.
but that's ambiguous.

558
00:27:58.944 --> 00:28:00.674
And Auster showed up?

559
00:28:01.780 --> 00:28:03.749
He prescribes him
peridine for the headache

560
00:28:03.782 --> 00:28:05.614
without a patient work-up.

561
00:28:05.651 --> 00:28:07.244
It's the worst thing you can do.

562
00:28:07.286 --> 00:28:09.221
It masks the
symptoms of meningitis.

563
00:28:09.254 --> 00:28:10.984
which is what the guy had.

564
00:28:11.023 --> 00:28:13.185
<i>We saved him... barely.</i>

565
00:28:14.626 --> 00:28:17.596
Now every time I see
Auster walk into the ER.

566
00:28:17.629 --> 00:28:20.258
I want to grab whoever I'm
treating and hide them in a closet.

567
00:28:20.299 --> 00:28:21.961
<i>(door opens)</i>

568
00:28:27.639 --> 00:28:29.631
Good afternoon. Dr. Simonson.

569
00:28:30.642 --> 00:28:32.076
Sir.

570
00:28:32.110 --> 00:28:33.635
Stone: That'll
be all. thank you.

571
00:28:38.050 --> 00:28:39.780
So...

572
00:28:39.818 --> 00:28:41.081
are we early?

573
00:28:41.119 --> 00:28:43.350
Stone: <i>We got what we
needed from Dr. Simonson.</i>

574
00:28:43.388 --> 00:28:45.755
An intern. Mr. Stone.

575
00:28:45.791 --> 00:28:48.852
<i>Are you planning on asking
the cleaning lady to testify too?</i>

576
00:28:49.861 --> 00:28:51.489
About the time I
threw the tissue

577
00:28:51.530 --> 00:28:53.692
into the wastepaper
basket and missed?

578
00:28:53.732 --> 00:28:56.793
Ed. please... Every
doctor in this country

579
00:28:56.835 --> 00:28:59.634
has to worry about
some shyster lawyer

580
00:28:59.671 --> 00:29:01.572
<i>suing for malpractice.</i>

581
00:29:01.607 --> 00:29:04.042
Now...

582
00:29:04.076 --> 00:29:06.841
we've got a prosecutor
looking over our shoulder.

583
00:29:07.846 --> 00:29:09.337
The next time I
write a prescription

584
00:29:09.381 --> 00:29:11.907
am I supposed to
ask the Supreme Court

585
00:29:11.950 --> 00:29:13.578
to vote on the dosage?

586
00:29:13.619 --> 00:29:15.611
Look. Stone. you haven't
got a chance to convict.

587
00:29:15.654 --> 00:29:18.488
but this trial alone can
stain Dr. Auster's reputation.

588
00:29:18.523 --> 00:29:21.236
Are you proposing we give him the
Nobel Peace Prize and call it even?

589
00:29:21.260 --> 00:29:22.990
No.

590
00:29:23.028 --> 00:29:24.656
Adjournment with an
eye toward dismissal.

591
00:29:24.696 --> 00:29:28.656
Because of Dr. Auster
a young woman is dead.

592
00:29:28.700 --> 00:29:30.726
A doctor. Mr. Stone.

593
00:29:30.769 --> 00:29:32.294
is not a magician.

594
00:29:32.337 --> 00:29:34.738
If you drove drunk. this would
be an open and shut case.

595
00:29:34.773 --> 00:29:36.742
When you practice
medicine. Mr. Stone.

596
00:29:36.775 --> 00:29:39.643
sometimes a patient dies.

597
00:29:39.678 --> 00:29:41.476
And when you're a
lawyer. Dr. Auster.

598
00:29:41.513 --> 00:29:43.277
some of the people you prosecute

599
00:29:43.315 --> 00:29:45.375
are convicted.

600
00:29:47.252 --> 00:29:50.188
Defendants index. 1983.

601
00:29:51.923 --> 00:29:54.119
Where are computers
when you need them?

602
00:29:54.159 --> 00:29:56.924
Here's a little job for you.
Keyboard every lawsuit

603
00:29:56.962 --> 00:29:59.193
ever filed in New York
County into a computer.

604
00:29:59.231 --> 00:30:01.666
Most malpractice
doesn't result in lawsuits.

605
00:30:01.700 --> 00:30:03.896
You got any better ideas?

606
00:30:03.935 --> 00:30:06.734
Go door to door. ask if anybody
saw Auster kill the patient?

607
00:30:06.772 --> 00:30:08.570
We're going to do that next.

608
00:30:10.475 --> 00:30:12.603
Ah. Aye.

609
00:30:12.644 --> 00:30:14.670
There. I just saved
us a lot of shoe-leather.

610
00:30:15.681 --> 00:30:17.149
"Stivic versus Auster.

611
00:30:17.182 --> 00:30:19.413
In re: the death
of Angela Stivic.

612
00:30:19.451 --> 00:30:21.317
age 11."

613
00:30:22.321 --> 00:30:24.756
When Dr. Auster's
attorney told us

614
00:30:24.790 --> 00:30:26.383
they'd offer us a settlement.

615
00:30:26.425 --> 00:30:28.621
my husband said. "Take it.

616
00:30:28.660 --> 00:30:30.094
It'll be over.

617
00:30:30.128 --> 00:30:34.122
We can stop thinking
about Angela all the time."

618
00:30:36.535 --> 00:30:38.766
We bought the apartment

619
00:30:38.804 --> 00:30:40.466
and the furniture.

620
00:30:41.540 --> 00:30:44.374
My husband sat
in the recliner <i>once.</i>

621
00:30:48.714 --> 00:30:50.307
I'm sorry.

622
00:30:54.720 --> 00:30:58.020
When Dr. Auster came
out of Angela's room

623
00:30:58.056 --> 00:31:00.491
to say they couldn't
stop the bleeding...

624
00:31:01.593 --> 00:31:03.425
I smelled liquor on his breath.

625
00:31:04.996 --> 00:31:06.794
<i>Bourbon.</i>

626
00:31:09.167 --> 00:31:11.966
All I wanted was
for Dr. Auster to say.

627
00:31:12.003 --> 00:31:14.336
"I killed Angela Stivic.

628
00:31:14.373 --> 00:31:17.935
the beautiful daughter of
George and Melanie Stivic."

629
00:31:20.412 --> 00:31:22.608
Excuse me.

630
00:31:26.084 --> 00:31:27.552
You know the difference

631
00:31:27.586 --> 00:31:29.919
between Auster
and a serial killer?

632
00:31:31.790 --> 00:31:33.622
The weapon.

633
00:31:42.367 --> 00:31:45.337
You objected to the
administration of meperidine?

634
00:31:45.370 --> 00:31:47.396
Raza: <i>I suggested acetaminophen.</i>

635
00:31:47.439 --> 00:31:49.908
but Dr. Auster grew angry.

636
00:31:49.941 --> 00:31:52.274
He said if I didn't like the
way the hospital was run.

637
00:31:52.310 --> 00:31:54.541
I should continue
my training elsewhere.

638
00:31:54.579 --> 00:31:56.605
Stone: <i>Thank you. Doctor.</i>

639
00:31:57.716 --> 00:31:59.378
Do you know how long

640
00:31:59.418 --> 00:32:01.910
Dr. Auster has been
practicing medicine. Dr. Risa?

641
00:32:01.953 --> 00:32:03.353
Raza.

642
00:32:03.388 --> 00:32:06.449
Um. I don't know.
25 years. maybe?

643
00:32:07.659 --> 00:32:10.993
And do you know where
he went to medical school?

644
00:32:11.029 --> 00:32:14.557
<i>Harvard. I believe.</i>
That's correct.

645
00:32:14.599 --> 00:32:16.295
How long have you been a doctor?

646
00:32:16.334 --> 00:32:17.734
Two years. sir.

647
00:32:17.769 --> 00:32:19.635
I see.

648
00:32:19.671 --> 00:32:21.936
And where did you
go to medical school?

649
00:32:23.275 --> 00:32:25.437
At the University of Peshawar.

650
00:32:27.279 --> 00:32:28.713
Thank you.

651
00:32:32.350 --> 00:32:34.876
Stone: <i>Dr. Mills. were
you present on March 15th</i>

652
00:32:34.920 --> 00:32:36.855
<i>when Suzanne
Morton was admitted?</i>

653
00:32:36.888 --> 00:32:38.516
Mills: <i>Yes.</i>

654
00:32:38.557 --> 00:32:40.753
And what was your
reaction when Dr. Auster

655
00:32:40.792 --> 00:32:43.261
prepared to inject Suzanne
Morton with meperidine?

656
00:32:43.295 --> 00:32:45.628
I said her chart showed

657
00:32:45.664 --> 00:32:47.656
she was taking phenelzine.

658
00:32:47.699 --> 00:32:50.965
Meperidine was contra-indicated.

659
00:32:51.002 --> 00:32:53.562
And where did you
go to medical school?

660
00:32:53.605 --> 00:32:55.233
Harvard.

661
00:32:56.641 --> 00:32:58.166
Thank you.

662
00:33:03.215 --> 00:33:05.013
Stone: <i>So in your expert opinion</i>

663
00:33:05.050 --> 00:33:07.349
the administration of meperidine

664
00:33:07.385 --> 00:33:09.286
in conjunction with phenelzine

665
00:33:09.321 --> 00:33:11.017
killed Suzanne Morton?

666
00:33:11.056 --> 00:33:12.615
That's correct.

667
00:33:12.657 --> 00:33:14.785
No further questions.

668
00:33:16.094 --> 00:33:18.188
But isn't it true you had to run

669
00:33:18.230 --> 00:33:20.256
a second toxicological screen

670
00:33:20.298 --> 00:33:22.563
to even find meperidine
and phenelzine

671
00:33:22.601 --> 00:33:24.092
in Suzanne Morton's body?

672
00:33:24.135 --> 00:33:26.366
That's because both drugs

673
00:33:26.404 --> 00:33:27.963
are unusual unto themselves...

674
00:33:28.006 --> 00:33:29.998
Thank you. Doctor.
And would not be found

675
00:33:30.041 --> 00:33:31.509
unless specifically requested...

676
00:33:31.543 --> 00:33:34.445
Thank you. Doctor!
Which they were.

677
00:33:34.479 --> 00:33:38.348
Isn't it possible that pneumonia
killed Suzanne Morton?

678
00:33:40.018 --> 00:33:41.816
It's possible...

679
00:33:41.853 --> 00:33:44.516
that death rays
from Mars killed her...

680
00:33:44.556 --> 00:33:46.548
<i>(audience laughs)</i>
but I don't think so.

681
00:33:52.397 --> 00:33:53.990
Dr. Auster must've spoken to you

682
00:33:54.032 --> 00:33:55.523
during the course of the party.

683
00:33:55.567 --> 00:33:58.731
Every five minutes.
"Fill her up."

684
00:33:58.770 --> 00:34:00.398
Nevins: <i>Was his speech slurred?</i>

685
00:34:00.438 --> 00:34:02.100
Not so I remember.

686
00:34:03.174 --> 00:34:04.836
Did he seem drunk in any way?

687
00:34:04.876 --> 00:34:08.438
I never saw anyone
hold his liquor better.

688
00:34:14.219 --> 00:34:16.984
Stone: <i>During your years
of research into alcoholism.</i>

689
00:34:17.022 --> 00:34:18.615
Dr. Walters.

690
00:34:18.657 --> 00:34:21.491
have you ever observed
people who appear to be sober

691
00:34:21.526 --> 00:34:23.427
but are. in fact. drunk?

692
00:34:23.461 --> 00:34:25.225
It happens all the time.

693
00:34:25.263 --> 00:34:27.095
It could happen to Dr. Auster?

694
00:34:27.132 --> 00:34:29.761
Objection. it could
happen to my Aunt Minnie.

695
00:34:29.801 --> 00:34:31.133
but it doesn't.

696
00:34:31.169 --> 00:34:32.728
Judge: <i>Sustained.</i>
(audience laughs)

697
00:34:32.771 --> 00:34:34.364
I'll rephrase the question.

698
00:34:36.274 --> 00:34:38.834
If a 55-year-old man

699
00:34:38.877 --> 00:34:41.608
weighing...

700
00:34:41.646 --> 00:34:44.013
185 pounds.

701
00:34:44.049 --> 00:34:47.451
<i>having consumed 10 shots
of bourbon in two hours.</i>

702
00:34:47.485 --> 00:34:50.387
<i>appears to be stone cold sober.</i>

703
00:34:50.422 --> 00:34:53.085
does that mean he is. in fact.

704
00:34:53.124 --> 00:34:55.286
in full possession
of his faculties?

705
00:34:55.327 --> 00:34:57.262
No.

706
00:34:58.697 --> 00:35:01.599
Now if that same 55-year-old man

707
00:35:01.633 --> 00:35:03.898
weighing 185 pounds

708
00:35:03.935 --> 00:35:05.904
has several drinks

709
00:35:05.937 --> 00:35:07.371
and he appears
to be quite sober.

710
00:35:07.405 --> 00:35:09.567
<i>and makes a mistake.</i>

711
00:35:09.608 --> 00:35:13.443
would that mistake necessarily
be caused by his drinking.

712
00:35:13.478 --> 00:35:15.811
or might he have made
that mistake anyway?

713
00:35:15.847 --> 00:35:18.476
Obviously that's
impossible to say.

714
00:35:19.584 --> 00:35:22.782
You'd have to be that
55-year-old man to know.

715
00:35:26.658 --> 00:35:28.490
<i>(audience murmurs)</i>

716
00:35:33.098 --> 00:35:36.262
We've got Auster drunk at
Suzanne Morton's bedside.

717
00:35:36.301 --> 00:35:38.202
prescribing the
medicine that killed her.

718
00:35:38.236 --> 00:35:39.829
Why do I feel like
we're on the ropes?

719
00:35:39.871 --> 00:35:41.549
Better go back over
every shred of evidence

720
00:35:41.573 --> 00:35:43.337
and find out what we missed.

721
00:35:43.375 --> 00:35:47.312
Because Auster's brilliant doesn't
mean he didn't do something dumb.

722
00:35:47.345 --> 00:35:49.678
And cheer up. we
got all weekend.

723
00:35:54.686 --> 00:35:56.712
Over the past five years.

724
00:35:56.755 --> 00:35:58.519
the state health
department has been notified

725
00:35:58.556 --> 00:36:00.184
of six adverse occurrences

726
00:36:00.225 --> 00:36:01.921
in the Urban Medical
Center emergency room.

727
00:36:01.960 --> 00:36:04.225
Adverse occurrences.
Nice phrase.

728
00:36:04.262 --> 00:36:08.165
There were people who died
for reasons not immediately clear.

729
00:36:08.199 --> 00:36:09.690
In all six cases

730
00:36:09.734 --> 00:36:11.396
no fault was found.

731
00:36:11.436 --> 00:36:13.371
Five of the cases
happened on nights

732
00:36:13.405 --> 00:36:15.282
Dr. Auster happened to
be in the emergency room.

733
00:36:15.306 --> 00:36:18.299
Interesting. not evidence.

734
00:36:18.343 --> 00:36:21.108
Suzanne Morton. Angela Stivic.

735
00:36:21.146 --> 00:36:23.615
a 25-year-old guy
with meningitis.

736
00:36:23.648 --> 00:36:25.742
now statistical anomalies.

737
00:36:25.784 --> 00:36:27.548
This is beyond coincidence.

738
00:36:27.585 --> 00:36:30.714
In the case of the Morton
girl. you cannot prove

739
00:36:30.755 --> 00:36:34.385
that he crossed the line
between criminal recklessness

740
00:36:34.426 --> 00:36:36.395
and unfortunate mistake.

741
00:36:36.428 --> 00:36:39.330
If he knew he was an alcoholic.

742
00:36:39.364 --> 00:36:41.890
then drinking
before going to work

743
00:36:41.933 --> 00:36:43.799
was criminally reckless.

744
00:36:45.003 --> 00:36:47.939
The crime did not take
place in the emergency room.

745
00:36:47.972 --> 00:36:50.339
It took place at
the cocktail party.

746
00:36:51.676 --> 00:36:53.770
Excellent.

747
00:36:53.812 --> 00:36:55.474
Okay. okay.

748
00:36:55.513 --> 00:36:58.642
I'm an alcoholic and I
know I'm an alcoholic.

749
00:36:58.683 --> 00:37:00.652
What do I do? Buy liquor?

750
00:37:00.685 --> 00:37:03.348
We've got charge receipts
for enough bourbon to prove...

751
00:37:03.388 --> 00:37:05.983
It proves he drank. it doesn't
prove he knew he was a drunk.

752
00:37:08.159 --> 00:37:09.787
Go to AA meetings.

753
00:37:09.828 --> 00:37:13.060
We can't canvas hundreds of AA
meetings before tomorrow afternoon.

754
00:37:13.098 --> 00:37:15.294
and there are no AA
meetings in his calendar.

755
00:37:16.968 --> 00:37:18.459
Whoa.

756
00:37:19.971 --> 00:37:21.701
What?

757
00:37:23.308 --> 00:37:25.937
Whenever he left town. he
called the office every day.

758
00:37:25.977 --> 00:37:27.605
Collect.

759
00:37:27.645 --> 00:37:29.910
Except on his last fishing trip.

760
00:37:29.948 --> 00:37:31.473
Stone: <i>Where did you spend</i>

761
00:37:31.516 --> 00:37:33.951
<i>the week of June
10th. Mr. Hoffman?</i>

762
00:37:33.985 --> 00:37:35.851
In Maine. fishing.

763
00:37:35.887 --> 00:37:38.152
Was Edward Auster with you?

764
00:37:48.833 --> 00:37:50.995
Was Edward Auster with you?

765
00:37:52.837 --> 00:37:54.396
No.

766
00:37:55.406 --> 00:37:56.840
Stone: <i>Did he ask
you to tell people</i>

767
00:37:56.875 --> 00:37:59.106
<i>that he had been
with you on that trip?</i>

768
00:38:01.112 --> 00:38:02.705
Yes.

769
00:38:02.747 --> 00:38:05.046
And why was that. Mr. Hoffman?

770
00:38:06.117 --> 00:38:08.677
He didn't want anyone
to know where he was.

771
00:38:10.054 --> 00:38:11.579
Why was that?

772
00:38:14.125 --> 00:38:15.855
He was embarrassed.

773
00:38:15.894 --> 00:38:17.522
And why was that?

774
00:38:19.964 --> 00:38:22.433
He had checked
himself into a clinic.

775
00:38:22.467 --> 00:38:24.265
Stone: <i>What clinic?</i>

776
00:38:24.302 --> 00:38:25.998
Hoffman: <i>The Colson Clinic.</i>

777
00:38:26.037 --> 00:38:29.030
What kind of clinic
is the Colson Clinic?

778
00:38:30.642 --> 00:38:32.873
<i>Mr. Hoffman?</i>

779
00:38:34.879 --> 00:38:37.110
It's a substance abuse clinic.

780
00:38:37.148 --> 00:38:38.616
(audience murmurs)

781
00:38:38.650 --> 00:38:40.312
Stone: <i>Thank you.</i>

782
00:38:48.560 --> 00:38:50.791
In his first group
sessions at the clinic.

783
00:38:50.829 --> 00:38:52.263
Dr. Auster told us he had

784
00:38:52.297 --> 00:38:54.459
gone through
college in three years.

785
00:38:54.499 --> 00:38:56.764
And he became Chief of Medicine

786
00:38:56.801 --> 00:38:59.498
at a major New York
hospital in only 10 years.

787
00:38:59.537 --> 00:39:01.199
Stone: <i>Anything else?</i>

788
00:39:01.239 --> 00:39:04.607
I believe he also mentioned
that he skipped fifth grade.

789
00:39:04.642 --> 00:39:06.975
(audience chuckles)

790
00:39:07.011 --> 00:39:10.277
Dr. Auster had very little
patience with our program.

791
00:39:11.983 --> 00:39:14.578
How long does your
treatment program last?

792
00:39:14.619 --> 00:39:16.315
28 days.

793
00:39:17.989 --> 00:39:19.924
How long did Dr. Auster stay?

794
00:39:19.958 --> 00:39:21.426
Six days.

795
00:39:21.459 --> 00:39:23.428
<i>He left against our advice.</i>

796
00:39:23.461 --> 00:39:25.987
Stone: <i>Would you say Dr. Auster
knew he was an alcoholic</i>

797
00:39:26.030 --> 00:39:28.261
by the time he left?

798
00:39:28.299 --> 00:39:30.734
He would never have come
in the first place if he hadn't.

799
00:39:30.768 --> 00:39:33.033
Stone: <i>I have no
further questions.</i>

800
00:39:33.071 --> 00:39:35.040
Are you positive?

801
00:39:39.477 --> 00:39:42.845
Now I am going to ask
you to limit your responses

802
00:39:42.881 --> 00:39:45.282
to my question to
a simple yes or no.

803
00:39:45.316 --> 00:39:48.286
so we can avoid these
subjective flights of fantasy

804
00:39:48.319 --> 00:39:50.447
that your last
statement exemplified.

805
00:39:50.488 --> 00:39:53.322
Do you understand my
request. Dr. Rasmussen?

806
00:39:53.358 --> 00:39:54.826
Yes.

807
00:39:54.859 --> 00:39:56.987
Good. thank you.

808
00:39:58.263 --> 00:40:01.290
Now. did Dr. Auster say to you.

809
00:40:01.332 --> 00:40:03.130
"I am an alcoholic"?

810
00:40:04.135 --> 00:40:05.194
No.

811
00:40:07.105 --> 00:40:09.199
In fact. didn't
Dr. Auster say to you.

812
00:40:09.240 --> 00:40:10.538
"I am <i>not</i> an alcoholic"?

813
00:40:10.575 --> 00:40:14.808
You must under... Yes or
no. Dr. Rasmussen. please.

814
00:40:14.846 --> 00:40:18.408
Did he say. "I am
not an alcoholic"?

815
00:40:23.855 --> 00:40:25.255
Yes.

816
00:40:27.025 --> 00:40:28.516
<i>(audience murmurs)</i>

817
00:40:28.559 --> 00:40:30.289
No more questions.

818
00:40:30.328 --> 00:40:32.763
Judge: <i>You may
step down. Doctor.</i>

819
00:40:34.098 --> 00:40:37.466
Stone: <i>Did Dr. Auster
discuss his drinking with you?</i>

820
00:40:37.502 --> 00:40:41.064
Anything that transpired
between Dr. Auster and myself

821
00:40:41.105 --> 00:40:43.370
is protected by
patient/doctor privilege.

822
00:40:43.408 --> 00:40:46.901
As well as patient and
doctor. you're friends.

823
00:40:46.945 --> 00:40:48.345
We are.

824
00:40:49.614 --> 00:40:51.742
Where did you have
lunch with him on June 7th.

825
00:40:51.783 --> 00:40:53.149
in your office?

826
00:40:53.184 --> 00:40:56.586
No. at The Four Seasons.

827
00:40:56.621 --> 00:41:00.149
Did you conduct your physical
examination of Dr. Auster there?

828
00:41:00.191 --> 00:41:02.490
Uh. no.

829
00:41:02.527 --> 00:41:05.656
Did you bill him for your time?

830
00:41:08.266 --> 00:41:11.896
No. it... it was a...

831
00:41:11.936 --> 00:41:14.030
<i>A friendly lunch?</i> Yes.

832
00:41:14.072 --> 00:41:16.473
So privilege is
not an issue here.

833
00:41:19.010 --> 00:41:22.970
Did you say anything during
your friendly lunch that upset him?

834
00:41:25.683 --> 00:41:27.083
Doctor?

835
00:41:28.519 --> 00:41:30.283
I... I...

836
00:41:30.321 --> 00:41:32.017
I told him

837
00:41:32.056 --> 00:41:34.218
that. um...

838
00:41:35.460 --> 00:41:38.828
if he didn't stop drinking
he'd be dead in five years.

839
00:41:38.863 --> 00:41:40.559
(audience murmurs)

840
00:41:46.704 --> 00:41:49.173
Thank you.

841
00:41:49.207 --> 00:41:51.199
Judge: <i>Does the
defense wish to begin.</i>

842
00:41:51.242 --> 00:41:53.734
or would you prefer to break
for an early lunch. Mr. Nevins?

843
00:41:53.778 --> 00:41:55.838
If it please the court.
the defense can bring

844
00:41:55.880 --> 00:41:57.280
its one witness before noon.

845
00:41:57.315 --> 00:41:58.715
Proceed.

846
00:41:58.750 --> 00:42:02.448
The defense calls
Dr. Edward Auster.

847
00:42:02.487 --> 00:42:04.046
(audience murmurs)

848
00:42:08.393 --> 00:42:11.522
And so the tragic
death of a six-year-old

849
00:42:11.562 --> 00:42:14.259
led to sight for one child

850
00:42:14.298 --> 00:42:16.233
and a new heart for another.

851
00:42:16.267 --> 00:42:19.169
<i>The boy who got the heart
is now the star shortstop</i>

852
00:42:19.203 --> 00:42:21.104
<i>to the little league
baseball team.</i>

853
00:42:22.106 --> 00:42:24.473
Nevins: <i>Finally.
how many doctors</i>

854
00:42:24.509 --> 00:42:26.341
<i>and immediate family
members of doctors</i>

855
00:42:26.377 --> 00:42:28.107
<i>have you treated
in the past 10 years?</i>

856
00:42:29.847 --> 00:42:32.840
(laughs) I really have no idea.

857
00:42:32.884 --> 00:42:35.444
Well. I do. I did some research.

858
00:42:35.486 --> 00:42:37.284
Over 300.

859
00:42:37.321 --> 00:42:39.688
So it seems you're
the kind of doctor

860
00:42:39.724 --> 00:42:42.193
whose hands other
doctors put their lives in.

861
00:42:42.226 --> 00:42:45.958
I certainly hope I've
lived up to that trust.

862
00:42:45.997 --> 00:42:47.932
Oh. brother.

863
00:42:47.965 --> 00:42:49.831
Defense rests. Your Honor.

864
00:42:49.867 --> 00:42:51.495
Judge: <i>Mr. Stone?</i>

865
00:42:51.536 --> 00:42:53.300
<i>The hour is almost up.</i>

866
00:42:53.337 --> 00:42:56.307
Could you hold your
cross-examination until after lunch?

867
00:42:56.340 --> 00:42:58.969
Of course. Your
Honor. <i>(gavel bangs)</i>

868
00:43:00.378 --> 00:43:02.813
Good job. I thank you.

869
00:43:50.094 --> 00:43:52.154
That many?

870
00:43:53.598 --> 00:43:56.158
So then you do think patients
should know as much as possible

871
00:43:56.200 --> 00:43:57.828
about the doctors
that treat them?

872
00:43:57.869 --> 00:44:00.737
Yes. of course. Where he
was trained. who trained him.

873
00:44:00.771 --> 00:44:02.433
Personal habits?

874
00:44:02.473 --> 00:44:04.704
I don't see why...

875
00:44:06.310 --> 00:44:10.008
unless it impacts on
his ability as a physician.

876
00:44:10.047 --> 00:44:12.744
Well. let's talk about that.

877
00:44:17.321 --> 00:44:19.256
Have you had a drink today?

878
00:44:19.290 --> 00:44:21.623
Objection. Your
Honor. relevancy.

879
00:44:21.659 --> 00:44:23.525
I'll allow it.

880
00:44:26.164 --> 00:44:27.860
Yes.

881
00:44:27.899 --> 00:44:30.494
Stone: <i>More than one?</i>

882
00:44:33.004 --> 00:44:34.734
Yes.

883
00:44:34.772 --> 00:44:36.570
<i>(audience murmurs)</i>

884
00:44:36.607 --> 00:44:38.735
How many more than one?

885
00:44:44.015 --> 00:44:45.745
I'm not sure.

886
00:44:47.018 --> 00:44:50.147
Do you recall. was it
between two and five drinks?

887
00:44:50.188 --> 00:44:52.157
I don't recall.

888
00:44:53.624 --> 00:44:55.422
Doctor. is it not a fact

889
00:44:55.459 --> 00:44:58.725
that you had six
bourbons on the rocks

890
00:44:58.763 --> 00:45:01.426
<i>at Chance's Pub
not 45 minutes ago?</i>

891
00:45:01.465 --> 00:45:03.331
Nevins: <i>Objection. Your Honor.</i>

892
00:45:03.367 --> 00:45:04.630
Judge: <i>I'll allow it.</i>

893
00:45:04.669 --> 00:45:06.103
Let's move on. Mr. Stone.

894
00:45:06.137 --> 00:45:08.197
Would you step into
the well. Dr. Auster?

895
00:45:08.239 --> 00:45:09.605
Objection. Your Honor.

896
00:45:09.640 --> 00:45:11.575
there's no need for
Dr. Auster to stand.

897
00:45:11.609 --> 00:45:13.544
Sidebar. please. Your Honor?

898
00:45:18.115 --> 00:45:20.482
What's going on. Mr. Stone?

899
00:45:20.518 --> 00:45:22.419
Does Dr. Auster look
drunk to you. Your Honor?

900
00:45:22.453 --> 00:45:24.012
What the hell is that
supposed to mean?

901
00:45:24.055 --> 00:45:26.991
I must be allowed to show Dr. Auster
is in the courtroom and he's drunk.

902
00:45:27.024 --> 00:45:28.686
Your Honor. I
strenuously object to this.

903
00:45:28.726 --> 00:45:30.126
Overruled.

904
00:45:30.161 --> 00:45:31.959
Proceed. Mr. Stone.

905
00:45:33.164 --> 00:45:35.724
Step into the well. Doctor.

906
00:45:41.839 --> 00:45:44.468
This is a New York City
Police Department manual.

907
00:45:44.508 --> 00:45:47.478
<i>I'm going to administer
a standard test</i>

908
00:45:47.511 --> 00:45:49.412
to determine whether a person

909
00:45:49.447 --> 00:45:51.313
is operating a motor vehicle

910
00:45:51.349 --> 00:45:53.181
under the influence.

911
00:45:53.217 --> 00:45:55.448
This is an outrage.

912
00:45:55.486 --> 00:45:58.183
Do as Mr. Stone
instructs you. Doctor.

913
00:45:58.222 --> 00:46:00.782
(sighs)

914
00:46:01.792 --> 00:46:03.727
Raise your arm

915
00:46:03.761 --> 00:46:05.923
to the level of your shoulder.

916
00:46:05.963 --> 00:46:07.932
close your eyes.

917
00:46:07.965 --> 00:46:10.298
and point to your nose
with your index finger.

918
00:46:28.819 --> 00:46:31.379
Dr. Auster. did you
appeal the verdict?

919
00:46:31.422 --> 00:46:33.948
No. I'm sorry... Nevins:
Could you please leave?

920
00:46:39.163 --> 00:46:41.132
Congratulations.

921
00:46:44.502 --> 00:46:46.334
How did you know?

922
00:46:51.175 --> 00:46:53.167
My father.

923
00:46:55.012 --> 00:46:57.208
Every day at lunch.

924
00:47:05.456 --> 00:47:08.392
<i>(theme music playing)</i>
